\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Never knew grandparents}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\cf0\revised\revauth1\revdttm651255813\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 
 (two died in concentration camps).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861  Both parents political refugees from Hitler\rquote 
s Europe though met and married in England. Mother (still in Manchester) b 1920, from Berlin; her father prosperous banker, migrated to Prague 1936; after German invasion, Quakers helped mother to England, as se
rvant to Southampton pharmacist. Father from Bohemia, his father had textile agency. One of three sons, eldest academic, specialised in chemistry of dyestuffs, went to Manchester 1936, working in factory; able to arrange for rest of family to come, father
 arriving 30 August 1939. Met mother at refugee club, married 1942.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Parents as refugees a strong influence. Grew up knowing political extremism \endash  left or right \endash 
 dangerous. Parents secular Jews; had enlightened views on capital punishment, homosexuality, foreign aid, etc. Sympathetic to later immigrants. Neither went to university, but book-readers, concert-goers, cultured. Politics discussed at dinner table. Lef
t-wing uncle came regularly, would debate, `so I grew up listening to political conversations\rquote . Remembers arguments over Suez, Hungary. By early 60s very interested in politics.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Ivor had one younger brother who went to Leeds College of Commerce, joined and inherited father\rquote 
s business, still in Manchester. Provide textile goods for supermarkets, hats and scarves etc, some they make, some they import.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Schools: prep school to 11, then passed 11 plus, free place to Manchester Grammar School [1956-63]. In sou
th Manchester, near his home. Big, 1400 pupils, all boys. There to 18. Teaching patchy. Took A level English, French, History.
