vik, and won}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 . Surprised by sudden election 1974, spent `every waking hour\rquote , but drew on it for publications over next twenty years.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Butler and Stokes had seen elections in terms of class, reinforcing people\rquote s loyalty to parties. Ivor showed part
y loyalties eroding because of socio-demographic changes, and parties adopting positions not accepted by own core constituency. Decline of semi and unskilled working class, and growth of non-commercial educated classes. More volatile results, bigger swing
s, transient protest parties.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 
Joint book with Tony King on SDP. Had played minor role in its formation, advisers, but advising it would not work. King had personal friendships with Shirley Williams, Bill Rodgers, Roy Jenkins. Book took longer than had party\rquote s existence.
