\par Data Archive was Blondel\rquote s idea, helped by Ian B
udge, launched with SSRC grant 1967, first director Alan Potter. Concept was a library/archive of primary data in computer-readable form, distributable to researchers. Surveys very expensive so with more users would be better value. Potter soon left for G
lasgow, then Ken Macdonald director two years, interlude co-directed by Budge. Originally every question catalogued, very time-consuming, assuming inquiries would be for specific questions, but in practice researchers wanted whole surveys. 
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Ivor became Da
ta Archive director 1974. Marcia Taylor gave him long file box of users, opened it expecting crammed with cards, found thin pack of a mere 25. Due for funding renewal 1976, knew must boost number of users, used networks. Most users not interested in resea
rch studies like Michael Young\rquote s, but in big government statistical studies, especially when repeated, as panel studies, Labour Force S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b0\f42\fs22\cf0\revised\revauth1\revdttm651255824\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 urvey, Nat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\deleted\f42\fs22\revauthdel1\revdttmdel651255824\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 tudy, Nat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 ional Food Survey, election studies.  Negotiated with government to deposit these. Turning point when s
ecured deposit of Census and Labour Force Survey. Saves government departments the work of cataloguing.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Technology changed, from punch cards to tapes and disks. Set up exchanges with archives in America (eg Michigan) and Europe (eg Koln), also Norway, Sw
eden, Italy. Regrets never had strong relationship \endash  eg research programme \endash 
 with Essex social science departments. Tried data archive representatives in departments, seminars, etc. Provided some data for summer school. Sociology then moving away from surv
ey-0based research. A bit more contact when Institute for Social and Economic Research set up. Ivor involved in this with David Rose, feels data archive presence was helpful.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\ul\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Head of Government Department 1982-6. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Previous Vice-Chancellors: did not kno
w Albert Sloman well. Not very approachable, austere. Admirable original conception of modern university. His difficulty with students partly that a new situation, few precedents, and lacked overwhelming staff support. Probably stayed on too long as vice-
c
hancellor, could have gone ten years earlier when university back in balance. In last years unwilling to make new moves. Excellent early appointments. Too slow to recognise growing importance of professional degrees; should have had law, accounting, etc, 
much earlier. Early in recruiting from overseas.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7684861 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\f42\fs22\insrsid7929874\charrsid7684861 Failure to expand rapidly in 1980s left Essex too small and vulnerable. Shaken by local community turning hostile, cut off from all but `good and great'\rquote 
 did not build goodwill in town or region. As new university on greenfield site had no local roots. Financially vulnerable, do need local support, and Sloman should have tried harder for this; stuffy, awkward.
